ABUJA  – The National Information Technology Development Agency (NITDA), in line Digital Literacy and Skills pillar of the National Digital Economy Policy and Strategy for a Digital Nigeria, has commenced the Digital Literacy and Skills Programme for States. The Digital States Programme, designed as one of the implementation strategies of the National Digital Economy Policy and Strategy for a Digital Nigeria, is aimed at equipping Nigerian youths with the necessary digital literacy skills that can facilitate Nigeria’s transition to the Digital Economy. A statement by Mrs Hadiza Umar, Head, Corporate Affairs and External Relations in NITDA, explained that specific areas of focus for the programme include: IT management of productivity tools; Understanding Digital Marketing and Basics of Content Creation; and Entrepreneurial Skills including Basics of Career Development. HOW NIGERIAN MEN CAN NOW NATURALLY STOP PREMATURE EJACULATION, LOW SPERM COUNT AND OTHER MEN'S SEXUAL NEEDS. MADAM ALWAYS WANTS IT BIGGER, STRONGER AND LONG-LASTING!!! Umar said the programme was aimed at training about 540 youths from each state of the Federation and the Federal Capital Territory, Abuja. She said it is expected that about 20,000 Nigerians will benefit from the programme. How FTZ Will Reduce Unemployment In Abuja – NEPZA Boss StarTimes Under No Winding Up Order – Pay TV Operator She said registration for the first phase of the programme has commenced on Monday 8th March, 2021. “The beneficiary states for the first phase are Gombe, Kano, Lagos and Rivers States. Schedule for the subsequent phases will be advertised in due course. “Further information and registration guidelines can be found on the NITDA Academy website: https://academy.nitda.gov.ng/public/digital-skills,” the statement explained.